ning to Audio -- t14. Reproducing Analog Pathologies in the Digital Radio Landscape: The Case of Greece -- t15. Almost 100 Years of Women in Radio: Where Are We Now? -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Editor -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the first books to examine the status of broadcasting on its one hundredth anniversary, Radio's Second Century investigates both vanguard and perennial topics relevant to radio's past, present, and future. As the radio industry enters its second century of existence, it continues to be a dominant mass medium with almost total listenership saturation despite rapid technological advancements that provide alternatives for consumers. Lasting influences such as on-air personalities, audience behavior, fan relationships, and localism are analyzed as well as contemporary issues including social and digital media. Other essays examine the regulatory concerns that continue to exist for public radio, commercial radio, and community radio, and discuss the hindrances and challenges posed by government regulation with an emphasis on both American and international perspectives. Radio's impact on cultural hegemony through creative programming content in the areas of religion, ethnic inclusivity, and gender parity is also explored. Taken together, this volume compromises a meaningful insight into the broadcast industry's continuing power to inform and entertain listeners around the world via its oldest mass medium--radio.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aRadio broadcasting. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBarber, John F.1 aBarber, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlaney, Joseph R.1 aBlaney, Joseph R., econtributor.4ct